# Java SDK Obfuscation — PRD & Implementation Notes

**Date:** 2026-04-15
**Scope:** PRD for Java SDK obfuscation, what we built to satisfy it, and how the ProGuard keep rules work in practice.

---

# Part 1 — Product Requirements Document

## Problem Statement

The Java SDK (`browserstack-ai-sdk-java`) ships as a JAR that any user can decompile with free tools (JD-GUI, CFR, Fernflower, IntelliJ's built-in decompiler). Without obfuscation:

- **Competitive risk (2026 reality)**: A competitor can decompile the JAR, feed the output to an LLM (Claude/GPT), and reconstruct a working clone in hours. Readable source = zero friction to copy.
- **Brand exposure**: The SDK is built on Langfuse internals. The `@@@langfuseMedia` string in `Media.java` reveals the upstream dependency.
- **Endpoint disclosure**: Hardcoded URLs (`https://evals-api.browserstack.com`, `https://evals-ingestion.browserstack.com`, `/api/public/otel/v1/traces-msgpackr`) and env var names (`AISDK_PUBLIC_KEY`) are visible as string literals.
- **Parity gap**: Node.js SDK (Rollup + javascript-obfuscator) and Python SDK (OPy) both obfuscate identifiers AND encrypt strings. Java was the only SDK without this protection.

## Goals

| # | Requirement | Success criterion |
|---|---|---|
| R1 | **Identifier obfuscation** — rename internal classes/methods/fields | Decompiled internal classes show single-letter names (`a`, `b`, `c`) |
| R2 | **String encryption** — encrypt all string constants in non-keep classes | No URLs, env var names, auth headers, or brand strings visible in `strings <jar>` output |
| R3 | **Preserve public API** — users' existing code must work unchanged | Demo app (`rag-context-propagation`) compiles and runs without modification |
| R4 | **Preserve ByteBuddy auto-tracing** — bytecode instrumentation must still inline correctly | OpenAI/Anthropic/Spring AI auto-tracing works end-to-end |
| R5 | **Preserve Jackson serialization** — API models must deserialize correctly | `sdk.datasets().list()` returns populated objects, not empty fields |
| R6 | **Zero config for new instrumentations** — adding Bedrock/Gemini/etc. should need no obfuscation changes | Package-level wildcards cover new classes automatically |
| R7 | **Zero source code changes** — obfuscation is a build-time transform | No `@Obfuscate` annotations or other source decorations |
| R8 | **Debug mapping file** — stack traces must be decodable for support | `mapping.txt` produced alongside JAR, shipped to S3 separately |
| R9 | **Parity with Node.js / Python SDKs** | Same level of protection: identifiers + strings + brand hiding |
| R10 | **Validation in CI** — catch obfuscation regressions before publish | Build fails if sensitive strings leak or public API breaks |

## Non-goals

- Control flow flattening (unnecessary complexity; breaks ByteBuddy)
- Whole-class encryption (requires custom ClassLoader at runtime)
- Protection against runtime debugging (any Java app can be debugged with agents; not the threat model)
- Unbreakable obfuscation (no such thing for Java bytecode; goal is raising attacker cost)

## Threat model

- **Primary attacker**: Competitor or customer who wants to understand how the SDK works, clone it, or extract hardcoded secrets.
- **Attacker capability**: Standard Java decompiler + LLM assistance. No runtime debugging of the SDK in production.
- **What we protect**: Architecture (call graph), integration surface (URLs, endpoints), brand association (Langfuse), internal implementation (batching, serialization, auth).
- **What we don't protect**: User's own code using the SDK (out of scope), runtime behavior visible via network inspection (visible regardless of obfuscation).

### Calibrated expectations — deterrence-grade, not security-grade

This obfuscation is **deterrence-grade**, not **security-grade** or **DRM-grade**. Be honest about what each layer buys you:

| Layer | What it defeats | What it does NOT defeat |
|---|---|---|
| **Identifier renaming** (ProGuard) | LLM reconstruction from decompiled source — variable names like `BatchSender.flush()` give away architecture; `a.b()` does not | A patient human reader who maps the call graph manually |
| **String encryption** (XOR + golden ratio mixing) | `strings` command + grep, casual decompiler inspection | Anyone who extracts `D.class` and writes a 10-line script to call `D.s()` on each encrypted byte array. The decryptor is right there in the JAR. |
| **Stripped debug info** | Stack traces matching exact source lines | Bytecode-level analysis tools |

The **real protection** is the *combination*: identifier renaming + stripped debug info make LLM-assisted reconstruction expensive (estimated 4-8 hours of skilled effort per significant component). String encryption raises the bar for `strings`-style scans and makes the decompiled output unscannable for credentials/URLs.

**Goal**: raise the cost of cloning the SDK to where it's cheaper to write your own from scratch. Not to prevent reverse engineering.

**For genuine secret protection** (API keys, license tokens, etc.): never embed them in the JAR. Always read at runtime from environment or secure storage. The SDK already does this — `AISDK_PUBLIC_KEY` is read from env, never hardcoded.

## Success definition

The obfuscation pipeline is successful when:

1. Running `strings` on the distributed JAR finds zero occurrences of: `langfuseMedia`, `Authorization`, `AISDK_PUBLIC_KEY`, `AISDK_SECRET_KEY`, `TESTOPS_PUBLIC_KEY`, `TESTOPS_SECRET_KEY`, `https://evals-api.browserstack.com`, `https://evals-ingestion.browserstack.com`, `/api/public/otel/v1/traces-msgpackr`, `application/x-msgpack`
2. Decompiled internal classes (`BaseApiClient`, `BatchSender`, `TraceSerializer`, `DotEnvLoader`) show single-letter class names and all strings as `D.s(new byte[]{...}, key)` calls
3. Demo app (`rag-context-propagation`) runs without changes, `curl` returns valid response, traces appear on BrowserStack dashboard
4. `/api/public/traces/{id}` returns full trace data proving end-to-end delivery
5. Adding a new instrumentation (e.g., Bedrock) requires zero changes to `proguard-rules.pro` or `StringEncryptTask`

