# Part 2 — What We Built

## Tool choice

We evaluated 4 approaches and chose **ProGuard + custom ASM string encryption**:

| Tool | Identifier obfuscation | String encryption | Cost | Maintenance per new instrumentation |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| ProGuard only | ✅ | ❌ | Free | None (wildcards) |
| yGuard | ✅ | ❌ | Free | Medium (XML config) |
| Zelix KlassMaster | ✅ | ✅ | $$$$/yr | None |
| **ProGuard + custom ASM** | ✅ | ✅ | **Free** | **None (wildcards)** |

Rationale: identifier-only (ProGuard alone) is insufficient in 2026 — strings are a roadmap for AI-assisted reverse engineering. Commercial tools (Zelix) cost $$$$. A custom ASM task (~500 lines total) gives string encryption for free with zero external dependencies beyond `org.ow2.asm:asm:9.7` (BSD, 50KB).

See full comparison: `testops-sdk/docs/plans/2026-04-14-001-java-obfuscation-comparison.md`.

## Build pipeline

```
compile (javac)
    ↓
shadowJar (relocate OkHttp/Jackson/msgpack to internal.*)
    ↓
proguardJar (ProGuard renames internal identifiers)
    ↓ outputs: proguard-output.jar + mapping.txt
    ↓
encryptStrings (custom ASM task: encrypt string constants + merge internal/ + observe/ from shadowJar)
    ↓ outputs: encrypted-output.jar
    ↓
validateObfuscatedJar (size check, plaintext leak check, decryptor presence, class presence, method presence)
    ↓
obfuscatedJar (final artifact)
    ↓
build/libs/browserstack-ai-sdk-java-{version}.jar       ← ship this
build/libs/browserstack-ai-sdk-java-{version}-mapping.txt  ← keep for debugging
```

