## Q: How did you decide what to keep in TestOps (and the SDK as a whole)?

I made decisions based on **which classes users import and call directly** in their code. The demo app (`rag-context-propagation`) was the primary reference for real usage patterns.

### Decision heuristic

For each class/member, ask:

| Question | If YES → |
|---|---|
| Does a user `import` this class? | Keep class + public methods |
| Does a user call this method directly? | Keep method |
| Does Jackson/Gson serialize this class? | Keep ALL members (`{ *; }`) |
| Does reflection look up fields/methods by name? | Keep relevant members |
| Is this bytecode inlined by ByteBuddy/CGLIB/etc.? | Keep ALL members (`{ *; }`) |
| Does it appear in stack traces users debug? | Keep class name |
| Is it an internal helper only called by SDK code? | **Don't list** → gets obfuscated |

### Each keep rule, justified

#### `-keep public class com.browserstack.aisdk.TestOps { public *; protected *; }`

Evidence from demo app:
```java
import com.browserstack.aisdk.TestOps;
TestOps sdk = TestOps.fromEnv();      // ← user calls this
sdk.traceManager();                    // ← user calls this
sdk.observe().init();                  // ← user calls this
```
Users call `TestOps.fromEnv()`, `TestOps.builder()`, `traceManager()`, `observe()`, etc. Keep public API.

#### `-keep public class com.browserstack.aisdk.Media { public *; }`

Users call `Media.fromBytes(...)`, `Media.fromFile(...)`, `.upload(...)` — needed for file uploads.

#### `-keep public class com.browserstack.aisdk.config.TestOpsConfig { public *; }`

Users may want to construct config manually:
```java
TestOpsConfig config = TestOpsConfig.builder().publicKey("...").build();
```

#### `-keep public class com.browserstack.aisdk.tracing.{TraceManager,Trace,Span,Generation,Event}`

Manual tracing API — users call these for custom spans:
```java
Trace trace = sdk.traceManager().trace(...);
Span span = trace.span(...);
Generation gen = trace.generation(...);
```

#### `-keep public class com.browserstack.aisdk.eval.* { public *; protected *; }`

The `sdk.datasets()`, `sdk.experiments()`, `sdk.prompts()` accessors return these client classes and users call their CRUD methods.

#### `-keep class com.browserstack.aisdk.observe.** { *; }` (note: `{ *; }` — keep ALL members)

This is different because **ByteBuddy inlines these classes into external bytecode at runtime**. If any member (including private) is renamed, the inlined code references a nonexistent method → `IllegalStateException`. Verified this empirically — we got `VerifyError` when `observe/` was obfuscated.

#### `-keep class com.browserstack.aisdk.eval.model.** { *; }` and `tracing.model.**`

Jackson uses reflection to map JSON fields to Java field names:
```java
@JsonIgnoreProperties(ignoreUnknown = true)
public class DatasetResponse {
    private String name;        // ← Jackson reads JSON key "name" → this field
    private String description;
}
```
If `name` gets renamed to `a`, Jackson tries to set `a` from JSON `"name"` → deserialization breaks. Must keep ALL members.

#### `-keep class com.browserstack.aisdk.exceptions.** { *; }`

User-facing exceptions appear in their stack traces. If `ApiException` is renamed to `a`, users see `com.browserstack.aisdk.exceptions.a` in logs — confusing. Also, users write `catch (TestOpsException e)` in their code.

#### `-keep class com.browserstack.aisdk.internal.** { *; }`

These are relocated dependencies (OkHttp, Jackson, msgpack). We also exclude them from ProGuard input entirely because ProGuard corrupts Kotlin stack map frames. This rule is defensive.

### What is intentionally NOT kept

These are internal and get obfuscated (renamed to single letters):
- `api.BaseApiClient` → `a.a` (internal HTTP wrapper)
- `tracing.BatchSender` → `tracing.a` (internal batching)
- `tracing.TraceSerializer` → `tracing.b` (internal msgpack)
- `config.DotEnvLoader` → `config.a` (internal .env parser)

The "keep" list is about **public contract + reflection targets**, not about hiding vs. not hiding. Everything not in the keep list still exists in the JAR — it's just renamed to be unrecognizable.

---

## Simple mental model

```
Public contract (users call these)   → put in a -keep rule with public/protected wildcard
Internal helpers (SDK calls these)   → don't list them → automatically obfuscated
ByteBuddy advice / Jackson models    → need { *; } to keep private members too
Relocated Kotlin deps (internal/)    → exclude from ProGuard entirely, merge from shadowJar
```
